[1] Uganda: healthcare worker, fatal
Date: Fri 1 Oct 2022 11:25 AM GMT+2
Source: Reuters [edited]
https://www.reuters.com/world/africa/ebola-kills-doctor-uganda-first-health-worker-killed-latest-outbreak-2022-10-01/


A Tanzanian doctor working in Uganda who contracted Ebola has died, the 1st health worker killed by the disease in the latest outbreak in the country, Uganda's health minister said on Sat [2 Oct].

"I regret to announce that we have lost our 1st doctor, Dr Mohammed Ali, a Tanzanian national, 37-year-old male," the health minister, Jane Ruth Aceng, tweeted.

She said Ali had tested positive for Ebola on 26 Sep 2022 and died while receiving treatment at a hospital in Fort Portal, a town about 300 kilometres [about 186 miles] west of the capital Kampala.

Authorities in the east African nation announced the outbreak of the deadly hemorrhagic fever on 20 Sep 2022, triggering fears of a major health crisis in the country of 45 million people.

There is no vaccine for the Sudan strain of the disease behind the latest Uganda infections.

The health ministry said on Fri [1 Oct 2022], before Ali's death, that the disease had so far infected 35 people and killed 7.

Ali was among 6 health workers who include doctors, an anaesthesiologist, and one medical student who have contracted the disease.

Ebola mainly spreads through contact with the bodily fluids of an infected person. The viral disease has symptoms including intense weakness, muscle pain, headaches, sore throat, vomiting, diarrhoea, and rashes among others.

[Reporting: Elias Biryabarema; editing: Kirsten Donovan]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[This is very sad. He was only 37 years old and among the doctors and healthcare workers initially reported as infected. He likely became infected before Ebola was identified as circulating. Our sincerest condolences. Please see more on the needs of healthcare workers below. - Mod.LK

